    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-special-angles-0-45-and-90-degrees" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Special Angles: 0, 45, and 90 Degrees</title>
        <objectives component="outcomes">
            <introduction>
                <p>
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>Strand</title>
                        <p>
                            2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                        <p>
                            2.4 Trigonometry 1
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                        <p>
                            Determine trigonometric ratios of special angles: 30, 45, 60, and 90 degrees using triangles
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Grade Level</title>
                        <p>
                            10
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                        <p>
                            40 minutes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
                </p>
                <p component="lesson-plan">
                    <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define trigonometric ratios (sine, cosine, tangent) for special angles. Explain that these exact values are derived from geometry, not from approximations.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Use isosceles right-angled and equilateral triangles to derive trigonometric ratios for <m>0^\circ</m>, <m>45^\circ</m>, and <m>90^\circ</m>. Evaluate trigonometric expressions involving special angles without using a calculator.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Simplify trigonometric expressions involving special angles. Solve real-world problems (e.g., dividers, geometry) using exact trigonometric values.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                    </p>
                </p>
            </introduction>
        </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
            <!-- Link to blurb -->
            <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

            <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
                <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/special-angles-0-45-and-90-degrees.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/trigonometry-1/step-by-step-guide_special-angles-0-45-and-90-degrees.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                    </p>
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </axiom>
        <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />


        <p xml:id="auto_5ddrt6ps">
            In this section you will use isosceles right-angle triangle to explore on how to find Tangent, Cosine and Sine of <m>45^\circ</m>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4d5m6erc">
           An <term>isosceles triangle</term> is a triangle whose two sides and base angles are equal.
        </p>
        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>15 minutes</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Grouping</title>
                    <p>Work in groups</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        This anchor activity activates prior knowledge of triangles, angles, and basic trigonometric ratios. Students work collaboratively to construct special triangles and discover patterns in their trigonometric ratios.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Facilitation Strategy:</alert>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>Circulate among groups to ensure accurate constructions.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Ask probing questions: <q>What do you notice about the sides?</q> <q>How do the ratios compare?</q></p></li>
                            <li><p>Encourage students to look for patterns across different angles.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Use student discoveries as a bridge to formal instruction.</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>
        <activity xml:id="auto_yl5qcpyi">
            <p xml:id="auto_su18cydk">
                <m>\textbf{Work in groups}</m>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_4fdy9300">
                <term>What you require:</term> A ruler, a piece of paper and a protractor.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ijeamlmh">
                <ol xml:id="auto_3do1nqnq">
                    <li xml:id="auto_ticd7612">
                        <p xml:id="auto_2w4rjagy">
                            Draw the isosceles right-angle triangle like the one below,(ensure that two sides are equal)
                        </p>
                        <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image label="Triangle17">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
                                % Triangle vertices
                                \coordinate (R) at (0,0);
                                \coordinate (Q) at (2,0);
                                \coordinate (P) at (2,2);

                                % Draw triangle
                                \draw[very thick] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;
                                \fill[white!70] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;  % Fill color

                                % Right angle box at Q
                                \draw (Q) ++(-0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(0.2,0);

                                % Angle label at R
                                \draw (R) +(0.3,0) arc[start angle=0,end angle=45,radius=0.3];
                                \node[right] at (0.3,0.2) {\footnotesize $\theta$};

                                % Labels
                                \node[left] at (R) {\textbf{R}};
                                \node[right] at (P) {\textbf{P}};
                                \node[below] at (Q) {\textbf{Q}};

                                % Extended Equal Side Marks
                                \draw[thick] (1.9,1) -- (2.1,1);  % Extended tick mark across PQ
                                \draw[thick] (1,0.1) -- (1,-0.1); % Extended tick mark across QR
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                           
                        </image>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_wfl4owmh">
                        <p xml:id="auto_qgrfxkyu">
                            Measure the angle that substend the Hypotenues and the adjacent that is <m>\theta</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_n7e6w2i9">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vxocg408">
                            Measure the length <m>PQ \, \text{and}\, QR</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_r44ifech">
                            What do you notice about <m>PQ \, \text{and}\, QR</m>
                        </p>
                        
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_ov31x6bs">
                        <p xml:id="auto_zu2vqvc0">
                            Find the following trigonometrc ratios:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_yahsezgf">
                            <ol xml:id="auto_2l247v9y">
                                <li xml:id="auto_erpu55cg">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_ni4thqqj">
                                        <m>\tan \, \theta</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_bzugpizv">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_ccgpxhlp">
                                        <m>\cos \, \theta</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_x0sb01ni">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_zldr2fzl">
                                        <m>\sin \, \theta</m>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0cm70fon">
                        <p xml:id="auto_vxkhr2b7">
                            Compare the value of <m>\cos \, \theta \, \text{and} \,\sin \, \theta </m>, How do they relate?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </activity>
        <exploration xml:id="exploration-trig-ratios-slider">
            <title>Special Angles (0°, 45°, 90°)</title>
            
            <introduction>
                <p>
                    Use the slider to investigate how the trigonometric ratios behave at special angles. 
                    Before moving the slider, make a prediction. Then explore the interactive and follow 
                    <xref ref="inst-special-angles-slider" text="custom">the guiding questions below</xref> 
                    to help you think carefully about what you observe.
                </p>
            </introduction>

            <figure xml:id="fig-trig-slider">
                <caption>Special Angles Calculator</caption>
                <interactive xml:id="interactive-trig-slider" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/special-angles-45.js">
                    <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-special-angles-45-90" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3"/>
                    
                    <instructions xml:id="inst-special-angles-slider">
                        <p>
                            Move the slider slowly and pause at each marked angle. Ask yourself:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    When the angle is <m>0^\circ</m>, what shape does the triangle form?  
                                    What do you notice about the opposite side?  
                                    What value does the calculator show for <m>\sin 0^\circ</m>, <m>\cos 0^\circ</m>, and <m>\tan 0^\circ</m>?  
                                    Why might these values make sense from the diagram?
                                </li>
                                
                                <li>
                                    At <m>45^\circ</m>, compare the lengths of the opposite and adjacent sides.  
                                    What relationship do you observe between them?  
                                    How does this relate to the values of <m>\sin 45^\circ</m> and <m>\cos 45^\circ</m>?  
                                    Why do you think this triangle is often called a special triangle?
                                </li>
                                
                                <li>
                                    As the angle approaches <m>90^\circ</m>, how does the triangle change?  
                                    What happens to the adjacent side?  
                                    What value is displayed for <m>\tan 90^\circ</m>?  
                                    Why might this value not exist?
                                </li>
                                
                                <li>
                                    Compare the three angles <m>0^\circ</m>, <m>45^\circ</m>, and <m>90^\circ</m>.  
                                    What patterns do you notice in the sine values?  
                                    What patterns do you notice in the cosine values?  
                                    How are these patterns reflected in the geometry of the triangle?
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                        
                        <p>
                            Discuss your observations with a partner and explain how the diagram supports the calculator values.
                        </p>
                    </instructions>
                </interactive>
            </figure>
        </exploration>
        <insight>
        <p xml:id="auto_c5n9lb2p">
            Look at the figure below;
        </p>
        <image width="50%">
        <latex-image label="Triangle18">
            \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define points
                \coordinate (R) at (0,0);
                \coordinate (Q) at (4,0);
                \coordinate (P) at (4,4);

                % Draw triangle
                \draw[thick,fill=white] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;
                
                % Mark right angle at Q
                \draw (Q) ++(-0.3,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0);

                % Label points
                \node[left] at (R) {R};
                \node[right] at (Q) {Q};
                \node[above] at (P) {P};

                % Draw angle arc at R
                \draw (R) ++(0.5,0) arc[start angle=0, end angle=45, radius=0.5];
                \node[right] at (0.4,0.3) {$45^\circ$};
                
                \node[below] at (2,-0.2) {\(1\)};
                \node[right] at (4,2) {\(1\)};
            \end{tikzpicture}
        </latex-image>
            
        </image>
        
        <p xml:id="auto_ngry7tzy">
            To find the tangent, cosine and sine of <m>45^\circ</m>, find first the length <m>PR</m>
            
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_aanayx8p">
            <md>
                <mrow> PR^2=\amp 1^2+1^2 </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp 1+1 </mrow>
                <mrow> =\amp 2</mrow>
                <mrow> PR=\amp \sqrt{2}</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_n12948pp">
            Therefore,
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_cv0m3s1m">
            <md>
                <mrow> \sin\,45^\circ=\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} </mrow>
                <mrow> \cos\,45^\circ=\amp \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</mrow>
                <mrow> \tan\,45^\circ=\amp 1</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        </insight>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>10 minutes</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Grouping</title>
                    <p>Whole class</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        After students have explored through the anchor activity, formalize their discoveries using the insight content. Walk students through the derivation of <m>\sin 45^\circ</m>, <m>\cos 45^\circ</m>, and <m>\tan 45^\circ</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Key Observations to Emphasize:</alert>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p><m>\sin</m> and <m>\cos</m> are swapped between complementary angles (e.g., <m>30^\circ</m> and <m>60^\circ</m>).</p></li>
                            <li><p>For <m>45^\circ</m>, sine and cosine are equal.</p></li>
                            <li><p><m>\tan 90^\circ</m> is undefined because it involves division by zero.</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Scaffolding Strategies:</alert>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li><p>If students struggle with Pythagoras, review the theorem with concrete examples.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Emphasize that these exact values are derived from geometry, not approximations.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Connect the ratios to the actual triangle measurements students made in the activity.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Use visual diagrams to reinforce the relationship between angles and sides.</p></li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>15 minutes</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Grouping</title>
                    <p>Individual work, then compare with a partner</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Work through the textbook examples on the board, pausing for students to attempt each step before revealing the solution. Then assign independent practice.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Additional Practice (assign if time allows):</alert>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol marker="(a)">
                            <li><p>Simplify: <m>\sin 45^\circ + \cos 45^\circ</m></p></li>
                            <li><p>Given <m>\theta = 45^\circ</m>, calculate: <m>\tan^2\theta - \sin^2\theta</m></p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Simplify the following without using tables or calculators:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <m>8\; cos \;45^\circ \;sin\; 45^\circ</m>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>sin \;90^\circ\; cos \;45^\circ + cos \;0^\circ tan \;45^\circ</m>

                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <m>tan \;45^\circ\; cos \;90^\circ - cos \;0^\circ sin \;90^\circ</m>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <md>
                                   <mrow> 8 \;cos \;45^\circ \;sin 45^\circ \amp = 8 \times \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} \times \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} </mrow>
                                   <mrow> \amp = \frac{8}{\sqrt{2} \times \sqrt{2}} </mrow>
                                   <mrow> \amp = \frac{8}{2} </mrow>
                                   <mrow> \amp = 4 </mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\cos \;45^\circ = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\tan \;45^\circ = 1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\sin \;90^\circ = 1</m> and <m>\cos \;0^\circ = 1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m> \sin \;90^\circ\; \cos \;45^\circ + \cos \;0^\circ \tan \;45^\circ = \cos \;45^\circ  + \tan \;45^\circ</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\sin \;90^\circ\; \cos \;45^\circ + \cos \;0^\circ \tan \;45^\circ = 1 + \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>\tan \;45^\circ = 1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\cos \;90^\circ = 0</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\cos \;0^\circ = 1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                            <m>\sin \;90^\circ = 1</m> 
                            </p><p>
                                <m> \tan \;45^\circ\; \cos \;90^\circ - \cos \;0^\circ \sin \;90^\circ = 0 \times 1 - 1 \times 1 = -1</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The angle made by the arms of an upright pair of dividers and the horizontal is 45°. The vertical distance from the horizontal to the vertex is 15 cm. Find without using tables:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The horizontal distance between the tips of the arms.
                            </p>
                        </li>  
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The length of the arms.
                            </p>
                        </li>                     
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since the angle is <m>45^\circ</m>, <m>tan \;45^\circ = 1</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Let horizontal distance <m>= x</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>tan \;45^\circ = \frac{\text{vertical distance}}{\text{horizontal distance} \div 2}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>1 = \frac{15}{\frac{x}{2}}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\frac{x}{2} = 15</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>x = 30\; cm</m>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Using Pythagoras theorem:
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <m>\text{Length}^2 = 15^2 + 15^2 = 225 + 225 = 450</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Length <m>= \sqrt{450} = 15\sqrt{2} \;cm</m>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                The length of each arm is <m>15\sqrt{2} \;cm</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
        <!-- STACK Questions -->
        <exercise xml:id="auto_0sfbl2x7">
            <title>Finding Trigonometric Ratios in a Right Angled Triangle (45°)</title>

            <introduction xml:id="auto_ved05rmk">
                <p xml:id="auto_pslvw8eb">Load the question by clicking the button below.</p>
            </introduction>

            <stack label="trig-ratios-45-degrees" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-4-Trigonometry-1/2-4-3-Trigonometric-ratios-of-Special-Angles-30-45-and-60/2-4-3-1-Tangent-Cosine-and-Sine-of-45/Finding-Trigonometric-Ratios-in-a-Right-Angled-Triangle.xml"/>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_0a7qikcl">
            <title>Determining the Length of a Divider Arm from Vertical Height</title>

            <introduction xml:id="auto_spmx7qw4">
                <p xml:id="auto_pj3nuonw">Load the question by clicking the button below.</p>
            </introduction>

            <stack label="divider-arm-length-45" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-4-Trigonometry-1/2-4-3-Trigonometric-ratios-of-Special-Angles-30-45-and-60/2-4-3-1-Tangent-Cosine-and-Sine-of-45/Determining-the-Length-of-a-Divider-Arm-from-Vertical-Height.xml"/>
        </exercise>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 4: Assessment – Exit Ticket</title>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>5 minutes</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Grouping</title>
                    <p>Individual</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                    <p>
                        Students complete the following questions individually to demonstrate understanding.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Exit Ticket Questions:</alert>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><p>Without using a calculator, find the exact value of <m>\sin 60^\circ + \cos 30^\circ</m>.</p></li>
                            <li><p>Given: <m>\sin \theta = \frac{1}{2}</m>. Find the angle <m>\theta</m>, where <m>0^\circ \leq \theta \leq 90^\circ</m>.</p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Answer Key:</alert>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><p><m>\sin 60^\circ + \cos 30^\circ = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} + \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} = \sqrt{3}</m></p></li>
                            <li><p><m>\theta = 30^\circ</m></p></li>
                        </ol>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </axiom>
        
            <!-- Simple exercises for exact values at 0°, 45° and 90° -->
            <exercises xml:id="exercises-special-angles-exact-values">

                <exercise xml:id="ex-special-0">
                    <statement>
                        <p>Find the exact values:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><m>\sin 0^\circ</m></li>
                            <li><m>\cos 0^\circ</m></li>
                            <li><m>\tan 0^\circ</m></li>
                        </ol>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <ol>
                            <li><m>\sin 0^\circ = 0</m></li>
                            <li><m>\cos 0^\circ = 1</m></li>
                            <li><m>\tan 0^\circ = 0</m></li>
                        </ol>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>

                <exercise xml:id="ex-special-45">
                    <statement>
                        <p>Find the exact values:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><m>\sin 45^\circ</m></li>
                            <li><m>\cos 45^\circ</m></li>
                            <li><m>\tan 45^\circ</m></li>
                        </ol>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <ol>
                            <li><m>\sin 45^\circ = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m></li>
                            <li><m>\cos 45^\circ = \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{2}} = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</m></li>
                            <li><m>\tan 45^\circ = 1</m></li>
                        </ol>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>

                <exercise xml:id="ex-special-90">
                    <statement>
                        <p>Find the exact values (and state any undefined):</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><m>\sin 90^\circ</m></li>
                            <li><m>\cos 90^\circ</m></li>
                            <li><m>\tan 90^\circ</m></li>
                        </ol>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <ol>
                            <li><m>\sin 90^\circ = 1</m></li>
                            <li><m>\cos 90^\circ = 0</m></li>
                            <li><m>\tan 90^\circ</m> is undefined (division by zero: <m>\dfrac{\sin 90^\circ}{\cos 90^\circ}</m>).</li>
                        </ol>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>
                
                <exercise xml:id="ex-special-sin-addition">
                    <statement>
                        <p>Given the addition formula <md>\sin(a+b)=\sin a\cos b + \cos a\sin b</md>, evaluate exactly:</p>
                        <ol>
                            <li><m>\sin 135^\circ</m></li>
                            <li><m>\sin 180^\circ</m></li>
                        </ol>
                    </statement>
                    <answer>
                        <ol>
                            <li>
                                <p> Using the formula with <m>a=90^\circ</m> and <m>b=45^\circ</m>:</p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\sin 135^\circ \amp = \sin(90^\circ+45^\circ)</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \sin90^\circ\cos45^\circ + \cos90^\circ\sin45^\circ</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 1\cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2} + 0\cdot \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}}{2}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </li>
                            <li>
                                <p> Using the formula with <m>a=90^\circ</m> and <m>b=90^\circ</m>:</p>
                                <p>
                                    <md>
                                        <mrow>\sin 180^\circ \amp = \sin(90^\circ+90^\circ)</mrow>
                                        <mrow>\amp = \sin90^\circ\cos90^\circ + \cos90^\circ\sin90^\circ</mrow>
                                        <mrow>\amp = 1\cdot 0 + 0\cdot 1</mrow>
                                        <mrow>\amp = 0</mrow>
                                    </md>
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ol>
                    </answer>
                </exercise>
            </exercises>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Differentiation</title>

            <table>
                <title>Differentiation</title>
                <tabular halign="left">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                        <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn triangles with measurements labelled. Use a reference table of special angle values for initial practice. Allow use of calculators to verify exact values. Pair with stronger students during group work.</line>
                        </cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <line>Complete all practice problems as described. Focus on memorizing the most common values (<m>0^\circ</m>, <m>45^\circ</m>, <m>90^\circ</m>) first. Encourage peer explanation of method.</line>
                        </cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Challenge students to derive values for <m>15^\circ</m> and <m>75^\circ</m> using angle addition formulas. Explore the unit circle representation of special angles. Investigate why <m>\tan 90^\circ</m> is undefined. Explore trigonometric identities using special angles.</line>
                        </cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>

            <paragraphs>
                <title>Extension Activity: Special Angles Memory Challenge</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li><p>Create a set of cards with angles (<m>0^\circ</m>, <m>30^\circ</m>, <m>45^\circ</m>, <m>60^\circ</m>, <m>90^\circ</m>) and another set with their trigonometric values.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Students work in pairs to match angles with their correct <m>\sin</m>, <m>\cos</m>, and <m>\tan</m> values.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Time the activity and challenge students to improve their speed.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Extend by including expressions like <m>\sin^2 45^\circ</m> or <m>2\cos 30^\circ</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </paragraphs>
        </axiom>

